ZooKeeper is a distributed coordination system used to manage:
  configuration
  leader election
  distributed locks
  service discovery
  metadata coordination

Quorum requirement
ZooKeeper uses quorum-based replication
Requires majority (N/2 + 1) nodes to operate
Example:
3 nodes → quorum = 2
5 nodes → quorum = 3
👉 This ensures fault tolerance

Throughput pattern
  read-heavy workloads perform best
  write-heavy workloads degrade quickly due to quorum sync

Failure handling is core strength
  session expiry
  ephemeral node cleanup
  automatic leader election

Znode size limit
  recommended: < 1 MB per znode
  ZooKeeper is NOT for large data storage

Znode - A znode is like a node in a filesystem:
Types:
  Persistent
  Ephemeral (dies when session ends)
  Sequential (auto-increment suffix)

Leader-Follower architecture - 1 leader , N followers
Writes: must go through leader
Reads: can be served by followers

ZAB protocol (ZooKeeper Atomic Broadcast)
Ensures:
  ordered writes
  consistency across nodes
  replication correctness

What happens if the leader fails? - A new leader is elected from followers using ZAB protocol, ensuring continuity.
What are ephemeral znodes used for? They are used to represent temporary state like: active service instances , locks. They disappear when session ends.
What is a watch in ZooKeeper? - A watch is a notification mechanism that triggers when a znode changes.
Why is ZooKeeper not suitable for large data storage? Because: data is stored in memory , znodes are small (<1MB), designed for metadata, not bulk data
What is the CAP trade-off in ZooKeeper? ZooKeeper prioritizes: Consistency ✔ Partition tolerance ✔ , Availability is reduced during partitions

Design a distributed lock system with ZooKeeper - 
Goal - Ensure only one client holds a lock at a time across distributed machines.
architecture - Clients → ZooKeeper → Ephemeral Sequential Znodes
hwo ti works - 
  Each client creates an ephemeral sequential znode:
    /locks/lock-0001
    /locks/lock-0002
    /locks/lock-0003
Step 2: Lock acquisition rule
  Client with lowest sequence number gets lock
  Others watch the node before them
Step 3: Waiting mechanism
  Example:
  P1 → lock-0001 ✔ (gets lock)
  P2 → lock-0002 (watches 0001)
  P3 → lock-0003 (watches 0002)
Step 4: Unlock
When P1 releases lock OR crashes:
  ephemeral node disappears automatically
  P2 gets notified → acquires lock
Failure handling
Client crash → ephemeral node auto-deleted
  No orphan locks
  Watches trigger re-election

Quorum ensures correctness
  prevents split brain
  ensures consistent leader

